Jack in the Box has sent shareholders yet another letter reiterating its confidence in its board of directors, including, and especially, chair David Goebel, ahead of its annual shareholders meeting Feb. 27.&nbsp;

Less than a week ago, the company urged shareholders to vote for all 10 of its board of director nominees, including Goebel, following a campaign from activist investor Sardar Biglari to vote otherwise. The company said such a vote would dampen progress from its Jack on Track plan introduced last spring to improve its performance.&nbsp;

However, Jack in the Box’s board was met with more resistance this week with proxy advisory firm Egan Jones recommending that the company’s shareholders withhold their votes from several directors, including Goebel. The firm argues that the company’s results have deteriorated since the Jack on Track plan was unveiled in April 2025, including a 7.4% same-store sales decline in the fourth quarter.&nbsp;

Now Jack in the Box is finding itself on the defensive again, mailing a letter to shareholders today reiterating its support for the board and Goebel, whom the company said, “brings critical expertise.” His removal, the company added, would “jeopardize the continued successful execution of 'Jack on Track’ as well as the value of shareholders’ investments in Jack in the Box.”&nbsp;

Further, the company reiterated that Biglari’s campaign is driven by his “self interest and anger at the board’s unanimous decision that he was not well suited to join the board.” Jack in the Box accuses Biglari of demonstrating a “pattern of contradictory and volatile behavior that repeatedly hindered constructive dialogue.”

Jack in the Box’s latest letter also reminded shareholders that, in addition to the company’s strategic plan, it has also appointed a new chief executive officer, chief financial officer, and chief operations officer, and is implementing an “orderly board refreshment process.”&nbsp;

“Importantly, we believe we have the right board and management team in place to build this strong foundation,” the company wrote. “In particular … David Goebel is one of the most qualified franchise executives in the quick-service and casual-dining sector.”&nbsp;

Goebel has been a board member since 2008. His industry experience includes chief operating officer, president, and chief executive officer of Applebee’s in the early 2000s, president of Santoku Restaurant Group, and board member of Wingstop.&nbsp;

Story Continues

Jack in the Box’s letter provides a chart outlining Goebel’s experience, both as an operator and in governance, and provides a quote supporting his reelection from Brinker International CEO Kevin Hochman, stating: “In my years working with Dave as my executive coach, his knowledge of the restaurant industry, deep experience as a CEO of a large multi-unit chain, and push to make sure that shareholders are at the heart of every decision made have been critical in my development as a leader and a key influence in our turnaround at Chili’s.”&nbsp;

Finally, Jack in the Box’s letter doubles down on the company’s decision to reject Biglari’s request to join the board.&nbsp;

The company alleges Biglari has “flip-flopped and demonstrated confusing inconsistencies” throughout its attempt to engage him. Biglari, the company further alleges, previously said the Jack on Track plan was a step in the right direction, but shifted that position after the board declined his request to serve.

Jack in the Box also claims it worked with Biglari toward a “mutually agreeable outcome,” meeting with him nine times.&nbsp;

“However, it is clear to the Board that Mr. Biglari is unwilling to be constructive,” the company wrote.&nbsp;

Jack in the Box also alleges Biglari has created a “pattern of volatile and at times abusive behavior,” including an accusation that Biglari “reacted with extreme anger upon learning that the board had not accepted his initial request to serve on the board.” Multiple directors, the company said, “witnessed Biglari threatening that his proxy fight would ‘get bloody’ and expressing directly to Goebel that he would come after him.”

Concluding its latest letter, Jack in the Box urges shareholders to “reject the kind of behavior that Mr. Biglari has demonstrated,” and vote for all 10 of its director nominees.&nbsp;

Prior to the annual shareholders meeting Feb. 27, Jack in the Box reports its first quarter 2026 results Feb. 18 after market.&nbsp;

